{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480708","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480708"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:49:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:49:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"98"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"98","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/98"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.45,0.32,0.08,0.1,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"98"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115908"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"98","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/98"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"98"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97904"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"1875"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"2823"},{"type":"tags","id":"3622"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9051"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5059"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7355"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11831"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12256"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35894"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38201"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38733"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39644"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41989"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44324"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46258"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49542"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115908","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115908"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 18-year-old Indigenous man presents to a rural General Practice clinic with a three-day history of malaise, mild shortness of breath and joint pain, initially involving his knees and ankles but now affecting his wrists and elbows. Three weeks ago he had a mild respiratory infection. He has no significant medical history, does not take any regular medications, and has no known allergies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. A rash with a target-shaped appearance is visible on his trunk. Cardiac auscultation reveals a grade 2/6 pansystolic murmur loudest at the apex. Joint examination shows swelling and tenderness of both knees, ankles, wrists and elbows.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn ECG demonstrates sinus tachycardia with a prolonged PR interval of 280 ms (120-200). The patient\u0027s ASO and anti-DNase B titres are consistent with a recent Streptococcal A infection. He also undergoes an echocardiogram, which demonstrates mild regurgitation of a bicuspid valve.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate long-term management for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intramuscular benzathine penicillin G every four weeks until age 28, then reassess","Intramuscular benzathine penicillin G every four weeks until age 21, then reassess","Oral amoxicillin 500 mg three times daily for 10 days, then reassess","Oral erythromycin 250 mg twice daily until age 28, then reassess","No further treatment required"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a clinical picture of an episode of acute rheumatic fever (ARF), complicated by carditis and mitral valve regurgitation. Diagnosis of ARF is made using a modified form of the Jones criteria, initially developed in the USA in 1944.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis (high-risk) patient has three major manifestations \u2013 carditis, polyarthralgia, and erythema marginatum; if carditis was not present, he would also meet one minor criterion \u2013 with a prolonged PR interval on ECG. Evidence of a preceding group A streptococcus (GAS) infection is confirmed with positive ASO and anti-DNAase B titres. Therefore, the patient meets the criteria required to diagnose an episode of \u003Cstrong\u003Edefinite ARF\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESecondary prevention of ARF involves treatment with benzathine penicillin G to prevent progression to rheumatic heart disease. Duration of treatment for definite RHD with cardiac involvement requires assessment of the patient\u2019s valvular disease. Findings on examination and in the echocardiogram are consistent with mild mitral regurgitation or mild rheumatic heart disease. Therefore, this patient should have prophylaxis for a minimum of 10 years after the most recent episode of ARF, or until the age of 21 (whichever is longer). Guidelines regarding secondary prevention are outlined in the 2025 Australian guidelines for the prevention, diagnosis, and management of acute rheumatic fever and rheumatic heart disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient described in the case stem is 18 and therefore a period of 10 years is a longer period than prophylaxis until age 21; thus, the correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Eintramuscular benzathine penicillin G until age 28, then reassess.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis therefore means \u003Cstrong\u003Eintramuscular benzathine penicillin G until age 21, then reassess \u003C/strong\u003Eis not the most appropriate management plan.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral amoxicillin for 10 days, then reassess,\u003C/strong\u003E would be an appropriate treatment for the acute episode of rheumatic fever, but does not provide long-term prophylaxis against recurrent episodes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EErythromycin can be used for prophylaxis in patients with penicillin allergy (\u003Cstrong\u003Ea regimen of oral erythromycin 250 mg twice daily until age 28, then reassess\u003C/strong\u003E). As this patient does not have any known allergies, this is not first-line management. The regimen also requires more regular adherence with twice-daily oral dosing, reducing compliance with prophylaxis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe recommendation for the use of prophylactic antibiotics in individuals who have had an episode of acute rheumatic fever is to reduce the risk of streptococcal infection and recurrence of rheumatic fever. Benzathine penicillin G also improves the long-term cardiac outcomes in patients with rheumatic heart disease \u2013 meaning \u003Cstrong\u003Eno further treatment is required\u003C/strong\u003E is also incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Benzathine penicillin G is the recommended prophylactic agent for secondary prevention of acute rheumatic fever.","In acute rheumatic fever with cardiac involvement, valvular assessment via echocardiogram is required to guide duration of secondary prophylaxis."],"references":["Menzies School of Health Research (ARF/RHD Writing Group). Australian guideline for the prevention, diagnosis and management of acute rheumatic fever and rheumatic heart disease (Edition 3.3). Rheumatic Heart Disease Australia; August 2025. Available at: https://www.rhdaustralia.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/Australian-ARF-RHD-Guideline-2025_August.pdf","Webb RH, Grant C, Harnden A. Acute rheumatic fever. BMJ 2015; 351:h3443. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26175053/","Schlossberg D, Samuel R. Antibiotics Manual: A Guide to Commonly Used Antimicrobials, Second Edition. Wiley Blackwell; 2017. Viewed October 2022.","Marek C, Timmons S. \u0027Antimicrobials in Pediatric Dentistry\u0027. Paediatric Dentistry (Sixth Edition). Elsevier;2 019, Pages 128-141.e1. Viewed October 2022."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97904"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"98"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97904","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97904"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-26T09:47:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-26T09:49:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"98"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115908"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updat